The client for this project was The Gaming Room, creators of Draw It or Lose It. They wanted to expand their trivia-style game into a multi-platform application that supported multiple teams, unique player and team names, and a scalable client–server design. In developing the documentation, I felt I did well at explaining the system architecture and justifying why a Linux-based server would be the most cost-effective and reliable choice, while still considering cross-platform compatibility for Windows, macOS, Android, and iOS. Working through the design document was helpful because it forced me to break the project into requirements, constraints, and architecture. This made me think ahead about scalability, security, and memory management before writing any code. If I were to revise my work, I would expand the evaluation section with more detail on the trade-offs between different operating systems, particularly regarding security and long-term maintenance. I interpreted the user’s needs for scalability and multi-team support by including features like unique IDs, the Singleton pattern for game control, and the Iterator pattern for managing teams. Keeping user needs at the center was essential to ensure the final design solved the client’s problems. My approach to software design was to move from requirements into architecture and design patterns. In the future, I would continue using techniques like UML diagrams, templates, and iterative design reviews to refine ideas and create clear, user-focused designs before coding.
